### Part 2: The "Dynamic `by`" Challenge (Re-entrancy)
Your idea: `for i from 1 to 100 by fn:`
Instead of adding a constant `2`, we call `fn(i)` to get the next step. I love this idea. It turns your `Range` object into a true **Generator**. 

But here is the architectural trap: **How does a bytecode VM call a function?**

In your `vm.c`, when you hit `OP_CALL`, the VM doesn't magically pause and execute the function in C. It pushes a new `CallFrame` onto the frame stack, updates the Instruction Pointer (`ip`), and lets the *main bytecode loop* start executing the function's bytecode. When the function hits `OP_RETURN`, it pops the frame and resumes where it left off.

If we put your dynamic `by` inside `OP_ITER_NEXT`, the C code would try to evaluate `fn(i)`. To do that, the C code has to set up a new `CallFrame`. 
But `OP_ITER_NEXT` isn't finished yet! It still needs to push `true` or `false` and update the stack. If it sets up a call frame, the VM will immediately jump into the user's function, completely corrupting the loop's setup phase.

This problem is called **VM Re-entrancy**. You cannot easily invoke the bytecode execution loop from *inside* a C switch statement case.

